rror messages have changed, which could make tests fragile. If I add an OSX classifier, it might not apply to Linux. I think I need to assess if “advisory_preparation” is a valid action when there's no concrete setup needed. Based on the guidance, I may need to go with “no_action” since it doesn't seem urgent but might still offer useful advice.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying guidance requirements**\\n\\nI’m trying to sort out how \\\"other test-code setup guidance\\\" should work if we decide on \\\"no_action.\\\" There's no setup needed, but the agent should still write tests to handle unavailability. I think the driver prompt might actually benefit from this. The user's request specifies to include environment variables and system properties in the agent guidance but not to restate deterministic entries. If no setup is required, I can mention that no properties are needed and account for the unavailable KQueue in the guidance.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"no_action\",\n  \"summary\": \"The resolved artifact already brings the Netty classes and transitive dependencies needed for Linux/Ubuntu tests; real kqueue availability requires macOS/BSD native transport binaries and is not something normal Ubuntu test setup can enable.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"No environment variables or system properties are required. Generated tests should expect `KQueue.isAvailable()` to be false on Ubuntu/Linux and cover the unavailable-transport path plus pure Java API behavior instead of trying to force native kqueue availability.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"Full available-native-channel behavior is not reachable on the standard Ubuntu runner because kqueue is a macOS/BSD transport.\",\n    \"Tests should avoid asserting overly specific `UnsatisfiedLinkError` messages; Netty 4.2.7 can report missing JNI symbols directly rather than the older 'required native library' text.\",\n    \"Adding `netty-transport-native-kqueue` would normally require an OS/architecture classifier such as `osx-x86_64`, which is not applicable to the Ubuntu runner and is not useful as generic test setup.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0458bda58a44923c016a3e65b7040c8193a8d4abf43deaef00\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 802, "output": 764, "cacheRead": 31232, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 32798, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1782474155089, "responseId": "resp_0458bda58a44923c016a3e65ab8b10819396d9991ed9a482b4"}, "toolResults": []}
